Investigating ComBat/CovBat for MVPA

Andrew Chen

Problem

To evaluate the effect of parametric harmonization methods on multivariate pattern analysis (MVPA), several studies (Chen et al. 2020; Fortin et al. 2018) apply ComBat or ComBat extensions to the whole data followed by splitting the data and training a machine learning algorithm. Then, they evaluate the performance of the model in the test set, which has been previously harmonized. This paradigm can provide insight into whether harmonization methods produce datasets that retain the associations of interest; however, it cannot be implemented in practice. For example, if the goal is to predict Alzheimers disease for a patient acquired on a known scanner, ComBat and its extensions cannot be directly applied to the patients data without already knowing if they have the disease.

Previously, we have implemented ComBat and CovBat while estimating coefficients only in the training set. While this mitigates the issue, it still does not provide a valid means to harmonize data without knowing the associated covariates.

Potential Solutions

  1. Remove scanner effects in test set without regressing out covariates, has a possible risk of removing covariate effect
  2. Use a propensity score or some kind of surrogate variable to provide a best guess for the covariates based on the test set data
  3. Treat the outcome in the machine learning model as missing in the test set and use an imputation method based on other covariates

Solution 1: Remove scanner effects without residualization

One simple solution is to apply harmonization in the training data then use the estimated scanner mean/variance effects to remove scanner effects from the test set. Performing the latter step without the test labels is not possible using the original ComBat model, but we can instead retain the mean of the observations.

We assume that the original ComBat model holds for the training data \(y_{ijv}\) \[y_{ijv} = \alpha_v + \boldsymbol{x}_{ij}^T \boldsymbol{\beta}_v + \gamma_{iv} + \delta_{iv} e_{ijv}\] where \(e_{ijv} \sim N(0, \sigma_v^2)\). Denote the standardized data \(z_{ijv} = \frac{y_{ijv} - \hat{\alpha}_v + \boldsymbol{x}_{ij}^T \hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}_v}}{\hat{\sigma}_{v}}\). Then we obtain our harmonized training set as \[y_{ijv}^{ComBat} = \frac{\hat{\sigma}_{v}}{\delta_{iv}^*} (z_{ijv} - \gamma_{iv}^*) + \hat{\alpha}_v + \boldsymbol{x}_{ij}^T \hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}_v\]

For the test set denoted \(w_{ijv}\) which can only include sites in the training data, we assume that these observations follow the same model \[w_{ijv} = \alpha_v + \boldsymbol{u}_{ij}^T \boldsymbol{\beta}_v + \gamma_{iv} + \delta_{iv} \epsilon_{ijv}\] where we also have \(\epsilon_{ijv} \sim N(0, \sigma_v^2)\) but their covariates \(\boldsymbol{u}_{ij}\) are unknown. We choose to remove the mean of each feature \(\bar{w}_{v}\) and use the estimates \(\hat{\sigma}_{v}\) from the training data. Our harmonized training set is then \[w_{ijv}^{ComBat} = \frac{\hat{\sigma}_{v}}{\delta_{iv}^*} \left(\frac{w_{ijv} - \bar{w}_{v}}{\hat{\sigma}_{v}} - \gamma_{iv}^* \right) + \bar{w}_{v}\] For CovBat, we propose a similar method for the test set where we remove site effects from the principal components of \(w_{ijv}^{ComBat} - \bar{w}_{v}\).

Evaluation

We evaluate the performance of this proposed method through a similar MVPA experiment as in the CovBat paper. That is we i) split the sample into 270 training subjects and 235 testing subjects such that both the train and test sets contain at least one subject acquired on each scanner, ii) train a random forests algorithm in the harmonized train set, and iii) assess predictive performance in the test set.

References

Removal of Scanner Effects in Covariance Improves Multivariate Pattern Analysis in Neuroimaging Data. bioRxiv, June. Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory, 858415. https://doi.org/10.1101/858415.

Fortin, Jean-Philippe, Nicholas Cullen, Yvette I. Sheline, Warren D. Taylor, Irem Aselcioglu, Philip A. Cook, Phil Adams, et al. 2018. Harmonization of Cortical Thickness Measurements Across Scanners and Sites. NeuroImage 167 (February): 10420. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.neuroimage.2017.11.024.
